metadata.name: Action; System #47
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of François Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl
License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Refrigerators and Wordsworth #18
metadata.description:
****
Haikus are easy
But sometimes don’t make sense
Refrigerator
****

DISCLAIMER: Programmatic syllable counting is a difficult problem. Occasionally, this work will generate sentences with one too many or one too few syllables. We have tried to make the syllable counting algorithm as robust as possible, but, due to the quirks of the English language, there will always be more cases that miscount. (And if you get 6 instead of 5, it’s value for money).

Originally made for January 28th, with the prompt “Generative Poetry”, this is a complete overhaul of the original throwaway Genuary project (https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/24355) for #genuary32nd. This ground up rebuild features new backgrounds, a new method of Haiku generation, and a brand-new syllable counting function. 

The Haikus are generated using a Markov Chain, which creates sentences based on a large database of haikus. The Markov Chain Method guarantees that the generated strings are locally sensible (as in, adjacent words will make sense together), however, the whole string won’t necessarily make sense. We feel that this whimsical sentence structure somewhat accents the style of the haiku, by providing (accidentally) artistic phrases. Afterwards, the strings are screened with a homemade syllable counter, which attempts to guarantee a 5-7-5 structure of the Haiku. The generated haiku is then displayed in a field of letters, with various color palettes and animations possible, which are displayed as fxHash Features. Try and collect the Legendary Matrix + Rain combo!

Credits to xiboon, and his excellent Markov Chain library, kurwov (https://github.com/xiboon/kurwov). This framework forms the backbone of the generation. The haikus database was taken from https://github.com/herval/haikuzao/blob/master/inputs/haiku.txt and https://github.com/sballas8/PoetRNN/blob/master/data/haikus.csv , and then cleaned by us.

metadata.name: Mur #39
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: 7VV1N5 #227
metadata.description:
GO BIG OR GO HOME.

After a week of minimalism code, our hero, the handsome artist Daniel, decided he needed something involving maximalism to reset the balance. Finding pairs to put together is satisfying.

Images will take 6-9 seconds to display and refresh between window resizing.

Use the z key or single click/tap to switch to "zoom" mode, which zooms in and fills the viewport; use z & tap/click to cycle through views. Use x and double-click/tap to go back to square mode.

Note: It doesn't work on Internet Explorer, because Microsoft. iOS is faster than Android.

-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

z, click, tap - Switch to & cycle "zoom" mode
x, double-click, double-tap - Switch back out of "zoom" mode.
h - Toggle high-res (slow)
s - Download and save image (takes a few seconds, longer for high-res)

metadata.name: BlockonBlock #115
metadata.description:
‘BlockonBlock’ is the precursor and reserve pass for the upcoming ‘Hashway ‘69 Revisited’ collection by pixelwank. 
Free mint for pixelwank holders on tezos - After 3 days any remainders will be opened up to the public for 2tez.  

‘BlockonBlock’ was a study of rectangles following on from the use of circles in Generacci. 
Placements & building sizes are based on numbers from the fibonacci sequence. 

I had a blast making these and I hope they bring the collector as much enjoyment.

'Hashway '69 Revisited' coming soon :)

23 colour palettes 
14 colour overlays 
21% chance of extra lines
Click the image or press ‘s’ or ‘S’ in live move to save a 3000x3000 png 

Thanks for collectin’ & shoutouts to Circolors for the support <3 

R.I.F.F. 
Remember it’s for fun

metadata.name: Balanced #105
metadata.description:
What does balance look like when viewed through the lens of pure mathematics? This is the question Balanced attempts to answer.

Each output is composed of a unique collection of blocks mathematically stacked to be in perfect balance.

This is my Genesis project. Enjoy!

Interactions:
1 - Reverse your stack vertically and re-balance.
2 - Toggle between square and portrait frame.
3 - Show center of mass. 
4 - Toggle the border.
5 - Toggle the background (color/transparent)
6 - Export image (2048x2048)
7 - Export image (4096x4096)
8 - Export image (8192x8192)

How it was made: https://www.jeffweber.art/balanced

metadata.name: Hatchet: Kagami #13
metadata.description:
Hatchet: Kagami (鏡) is the third piece in Hatchet; a generative art series that hatches an arrangement of segmented polygons generated via a Voronoi diagram. Kagami (Japanese for 'mirror') arranges it's polygons in reflected symmetry, creating patterns reminiscent of kaleidoscopes and snowflakes. Mixed color palettes alternate between reflections to incorporate a level of asymmetry. As opposed to previous Hatchet pieces, the chance of generating a light and dark background is equal.

All pieces in Hatchet are composed to emulate the aesthetic of colored pencils on paper. Each piece is capable of exporting its hatch lines as a well-labeled SVG document. This will allow collectors interested in plotting to create physical renditions of their iteration.

The following key-press actions are supported on the token:
- 'r': Animate the erasure and re-drawing of the hatch lines.
- 's': Export the SVG document describing the arrangement of hatch lines.

metadata.name: Particularization #96
metadata.description:
“Particularization” is the seventh collection released as a part of NeoMent's "Abandoned Reality" series.

All concepts can be viewed from different levels. You can focus on the details, leaving out the generalized result but understanding the finer points. Or you could emphasize the concept as a whole, comprehending it well overall but missing out on the specifics. It's impossible to choose both, you have to figure out which approach works best for each scenario.

metadata.name: Alienpillars #174
metadata.description:
"A rare type of bug that supposedly arrived on a cargo ship is destroying crops on planet Uctumi, in the binary system of Extronium. A wide variety of very resistant subspecies has mutated and it is necessary to study and identify all of them to obtain a gen-activated pesticide that will work on all of their variations. The pest department of the Uctumi central government is working hard on it, and they say that these strange critters are probably related to similar species that inhabited the planet Earth of the Solar system a long time ago and have spread over the galaxy."

My second piece using the p5.js raymarcher I wrote. The drawing is made of circles and lines based on the 3D data. I wanted to try something hairy as it's easy to draw lines aligned to the surface normal with this method. I also used a shader for the frame and the glitchy/sketch features.

Features 

body color: green-red-purple-yellow-blue-black
body tone: dark-light
spots color: orange-green-blue-yellow-white
hair tips: yes-no
hair #1: short-medium-long
hair #2: short-medium-long
head size: small-medium-large
head shape: long-spherical-wide
glitchy mode: 10% chance
sketch mode: 9% chance
